## Request/Response Validation

### Request Validation

- Validate Content-Type matches declared consumes
- Validate request body against schema (required fields, types, formats)
- Validate path and query parameters
- Reject unknown query parameters if `additionalProperties: false`
- Return 400 with RFC 7807 body on validation failure

### Response Validation

- Validate response body against schema before sending (development/staging)
- Optional in production for performance; use in tests
- Log validation failures; do not expose to client

### Validation Error Format

```json
{
  "type": "https://api.example.com/errors/validation",
  "title": "Validation Error",
  "status": 400,
  "detail": "Request body validation failed",
  "errors": [
    {
      "field": "/body/email",
      "message": "Invalid email format"
    },
    {
      "field": "/body/age",
      "message": "Must be >= 0"
    }
  ]
}
```

---

## Implementation Checklist

When using OpenAPI:

- [ ] Spec exists before or alongside implementation
- [ ] Linter runs in CI (Spectral or equivalent)
- [ ] All operations have operationId, tags, descriptions
- [ ] Request/response schemas are complete
- [ ] Validation middleware or equivalent validates requests
- [ ] Generated code is regenerated when spec changes
- [ ] Spec is versioned with API (e.g., in same repo, tagged)

---

## Anti-Patterns

| Anti-Pattern | Why It's Bad | Correct Approach |
|--------------|--------------|------------------|
| Code-first, spec generated after | Spec may drift from implementation | Spec-first |
| No linting | Inconsistent, invalid specs | Spectral in CI |
| Manual client code | Drift from spec, more maintenance | Generate from spec |
| No request validation | Invalid requests reach handlers | Validate at edge |
| anyOf/oneOf without discriminator | Unclear which variant | Use discriminator |
